1)Local variables and instance variables difference and are they synchronised are not 
Ans)
| Feature                             | Local Variables                                                    | Instance Variables                                                                 |
| ----------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------ | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Where declared**                  | Inside a method, constructor, or block                             | Inside a class but outside methods                                                 |
| **Scope**                           | Only within the method/block where declared                        | Accessible to all instance methods of the object                                   |
| **Lifetime**                        | Created when method starts, destroyed when method ends             | Exists as long as the object exists                                                |
| **Memory location**                 | Stored in **stack memory**                                         | Stored in **heap memory** as part of the object                                    |
| **Default value**                   | ❌ No default value – must be initialized before use                | ✅ Gets default values (0, null, false, etc.)                                       |
| **Access modifiers**                | ❌ Not allowed (no public/private)                                  | ✅ Allowed (public, private, protected, default)                                    |
| **Synchronization / Thread safety** | Usually **thread-safe** because each thread has its own stack copy | **Not thread-safe by default** because multiple threads may access the same object |

Synchronization in Java
Local variables:
They do not need synchronization because each thread works with its own copy.

Instance variables:
They are shared between threads, so they may require synchronization (using synchronized, locks, etc.) if multiple threads modify them.

Example
class Example {
    int count = 0; // instance variable

    void increment() {
        int temp = 0; // local variable
        temp++;
        count++;
    }
}
