4) Arraylist linked list diff, Linked list explain
ANS) ArrayList uses dynamic array, LinkedList uses doubly linked nodes. ArrayList is faster for access, LinkedList is faster for insertion/deletion.
| Feature                     | ArrayList         | LinkedList             |
| --------------------------- | ----------------- | ---------------------- |
| Internal Structure          | Dynamic array     | Doubly linked list     |
| Memory Storage              | Continuous memory | Non-continuous memory  |
| Access Time                 | Fast (O(1))       | Slow (O(n))            |
| Insertion/Deletion (middle) | Slow              | Fast                   |
| Memory Usage                | Less              | More (extra pointers)  |
| Best Use                    | Data retrieval    | Frequent insert/delete |

Example
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.LinkedList;

ArrayList<String> list1 = new ArrayList<>();
LinkedList<String> list2 = new LinkedList<>();

ArrayList → like an array that can grow
LinkedList → like a chain of nodes connected by links

2️⃣ LinkedList Explanation

A LinkedList is a linear data structure where elements are stored as nodes.
Each node contains:
Data
Reference (pointer) to the next node
Reference to the previous node (in doubly linked list)

Structure:

[Prev | Data | Next] <-> [Prev | Data | Next] <-> [Prev | Data | Next]

Example:
10 -> 20 -> 30 -> 40

Here:

10 points to 20
20 points to 30
30 points to 40

3️⃣ Types of LinkedList (Concept)

1️⃣ Singly Linked List

10 -> 20 -> 30 -> 40 -> null

Each node points only to the next node.

2️⃣ Doubly Linked List (Used in Java LinkedList)

null <- 10 <-> 20 <-> 30 <-> 40 -> null

Each node has:
previous pointer
next pointer

3️⃣ Circular Linked List

10 -> 20 -> 30 -> 40
 ^               |
 |_______________|

Last node points back to the first node.

4️⃣ LinkedList Example in Java
import java.util.LinkedList;

public class Example {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        LinkedList<Integer> list = new LinkedList<>();

        list.add(10);
        list.add(20);
        list.add(30);

        System.out.println(list);
    }
}

Output:

[10, 20, 30]
5️⃣ When to Use LinkedList

Use LinkedList when:

Many insertions/deletions
Data size changes frequently
You don't need fast random access
Use ArrayList when:
You need fast access by index
Mostly reading data

