Rest template vs feign  client diff
RestTemplate is a synchronous HTTP client where we manually write REST calls, while Feign Client is a declarative REST client
where we define interfaces and Spring automatically handles the HTTP communication.

1️⃣ RestTemplate
RestTemplate is a synchronous HTTP client used to call REST services.
You must manually write the request details like URL, method, headers, etc.
Example
import org.springframework.web.client.RestTemplate;

RestTemplate restTemplate = new RestTemplate();

String url = "http://localhost:8081/users/1";

User user = restTemplate.getForObject(url, User.class);
Characteristics:
Imperative style,More boilerplate code,Manually manage endpoints,Older approach (now replaced by WebClient in many cases)

2️⃣ Feign Client
Feign Client is a declarative REST client.
You just define an interface, and Spring automatically creates the implementation.

Example
@FeignClient(name = "user-service")
public interface UserClient {

    @GetMapping("/users/{id}")
    User getUser(@PathVariable int id);
}

Usage:
User user = userClient.getUser(1);
Characteristics
Declarative,Less code,Better for microservices,Works easily with service discovery (Eureka)

| Feature               | RestTemplate       | Feign Client               |
| --------------------- | ------------------ | -------------------------- |
| Type                  | Imperative         | Declarative                |
| Code Size             | More code          | Less code                  |
| Implementation        | Manual HTTP calls  | Interface-based            |
| Microservices Support | Limited            | Excellent                  |
| Load Balancing        | Needs extra config | Built-in with Spring Cloud |
| Readability           | Lower              | Higher                     |

4️⃣ Example Comparison
RestTemplate
String url = "http://order-service/orders/1";
Order order = restTemplate.getForObject(url, Order.class);
Feign Client
@FeignClient("order-service")
interface OrderClient {
    @GetMapping("/orders/{id}")
    Order getOrder(@PathVariable int id);
}

Usage:

orderClient.getOrder(1);
5️⃣ When to Use

Use RestTemplate when:
Simple API calls
Small applications
Use Feign Client when:
Microservices architecture
Service-to-service communication
Cleaner code required
