User registration implementation 
Ans)User registration in Spring Boot follows a simple flow.
First, the client sends registration data like username, email, and password to a REST API endpoint.
The request goes to the controller, which forwards it to the service layer.
In the service layer, I validate the data and check if the user already exists.
Then I encrypt the password using BCrypt for security.
After that, I save the user details in the database using the repository layer.
Finally, I return a success response to the client.

“When a user tries to log in, they send their username/email and password to the backend.
The backend first verifies the credentials using Spring Security.
If the credentials are valid, the server generates a JWT token and sends it back to the client.
For subsequent requests, the client includes this JWT token in the Authorization header.
Then, for every request, the backend validates the JWT token to check if it is valid and not expired before allowing access to protected resources

JWT is not used to validate login—it is generated after login and used to authorize subsequent requests
